web_content_2 => UTF-8 string (2601) "<div><div>The Irrigation Association (IA) is the leading organization for al...
$value['web_content_2']
<div><div>The Irrigation Association (IA) is the leading organization
for all things irrigation; they are focused on educating the public on sound
practices and water management, define best practices for effective water
management, promote efficient irrigation technology, and more. Please visit
IA’s website to see various solutions and ways to get involved at <a href="https://www.irrigation.org/IA/About/Strategic_Plan/IA/About/Strategic-Plan.aspx" target="_blank">Irrigation Association</a>.<o:p></o:p></div>

<div>To explore nationwide cost-share and technical assistance
programs that help farmers improve irrigation infrastructure, visit the USDA
Environmental Quality Incentives Program (EQIP) portal at<a href="https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/programs-initiatives/eqip-environmental-quality-incentives" target="_blank"> USDA</a>. EQIP provides financial support for practices
like drip irrigation, soil moisture sensors, and water-saving upgrades.
Priority is often given to underserved and socially disadvantaged producers,
and local NRCS offices can help guide applicants through eligibility
requirements and practice selection. QIP is a key tool for small-scale and
resource-limited farmers to sustainably modernize their operations.<o:p></o:p></div>

<div>For integrated water management support across drought-prone
regions, see the NRCS WaterSMART Initiative at <a href="https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/programs-initiatives/watersmart" target="_blank">NRCS</a>.
This initiative focuses on irrigation modernization, precision agriculture, and
improving soil moisture retention through advanced water management practices.
It often complements EQIP funding and is especially beneficial for farms
located in areas facing chronic water shortages. Regional project partnerships
may be available through your state’s conservation districts.<o:p></o:p></div>

<div>To learn how underserved and small-scale farmers are already
reducing water use and improving resilience, read farmer success stories
at <a href="https://ucanr.edu/site/fresno-uc-anr-climate-smart-agriculture" target="_blank">University of California ANR</a>. UC ANR’s Climate-Smart
Agriculture program has helped farmers adopt drip systems, automation, and
scheduling tools, often with grant support and local advisor guidance. These
stories highlight real-world applications of affordable, practical irrigation
changes that lead to measurable savings and long-term sustainability—especially
for farms with limited resources.<o:p></o:p></div>
